\section*{\faArrowAltCircleRight[regular] \textcolor{blue}{Question}}

\hspace{1cm} The following covariance matrix is estimated for a sample of 28 observations:

\begin{gather*}
S =
\begin{bmatrix}
128.72 & 61.4076 & -21.0211 \\
61.4076 & 56.9259 & -28.2963 \\
-21.0211 & -28.2963 & 63.5344
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{gather*}

The calculated mean values are $(8.8591, 4.50, 0.8571)$ and test whether these values agree with the assigned values $(5, 1, 0.2)$.

\section*{\faArrowAltCircleRight[regular] \textcolor{blue}{R Program}}

<<>>=
S <- matrix(c(128.72, 61.4076, -21.0211,
              61.4076, 56.9259, -28.2963,
              -21.0211, -28.2963, 63.5344), nrow = 3, ncol = 3, byrow = TRUE)
@

\dice{1} The test statistic for testing $H_0 : \utilde{\mu} = (5, 1, 0.2)'$ against $H_1 : \utilde{\mu} \neq (5, 1, 0.2)'$ is $$n(\overline{\utilde{X}} - \mu_0)' \Sigma^{-1} (\overline{\utilde{X}} - \mu_0).$$

Under $H_0$, the test statistic has $\chi_{3}^{2}$ distribution.

<<>>=
n <- 28
x_bar <- matrix(c(8.8591, 4.50, 0.8571), nrow = 3, ncol = 1, byrow = TRUE)
mu_0 <- matrix(c(5, 1, 0.2), nrow = 3, ncol = 1, byrow = TRUE)
@

<<>>=
observed <- n %*% t(x_bar - mu_0) %*% solve(S) %*% (x_bar - mu_0)
observed
@

<<>>=
qchisq(0.05, 3, lower.tail = FALSE)
@

\section*{\faArrowAltCircleRight[regular] \textcolor{blue}{Conclusion}}

Observed value of the test statistic is greater than $\chi_{0.05, 3}^{2} = \Sexpr{qchisq(0.05, 3, lower.tail = FALSE)}$. So in light of the sample, we reject $H_0$ at $5\%$ level of significance.

